TY  - JOUR
T1  - Graciela Chichilnisky's model of North-South trade
AU  - Lysy, Frank J.
JO  - Journal of Development Economics
VL  - 18
IS  - 2
SP  - 503
EP  - 539
PY  - 1985
DA  - 1985/08/01/
SN  - 0304-3878
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3878(85)90071-9
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304387885900719
AB  - The model of the effects of North-South trade set out by Chichilnisky in the April, 1981, issue of the Journal of Development Economics, is shown to contain a number of errors. The model is presented anew in this note. After corrections are made, one can still obtain results similar in spirit to some of those Chichilnisky tried to derive, although the interpretation of the cause of the results must be substantially altered. In particular, it is shown that for appropriate parameter values in this model, one will find that it is possible for an increase in the demand for the good the North exports to lead to: (1) a worsening of the terms of trade for the South, (2) a worsening of the distribution of factor incomes in the North and in the South, (3) a reduction in the total export revenues of the South, and (4) at the same time an increase in the physical volume of the South's exports. The cause is, in essence, a shift in world demand from the good the South exports to the good the North exports, which leads to a terms of trade loss for the South. Income effects following from the terms of trade loss then lead to a situation where the South's own demand for its export good falls by more than its supply, thus leading to the preverse effect of an increase in the volume of its exports. The paper also considers the model of Chichilnisky and Cole (1978). This model is similar to that of Chichilnisky (1981), and is used to examine the same issues, but is ‘closed’ in a different way. It is shown that this second model may give similar results as the first, but that also a quite different set of results is now possible. Closure is therefore shown to play a key role.
ER  - 

