AB  - Sector share response coefficients relative to conventional and ‘real” GDP per capita are compared in cross-section models of production structure specified by Chenery and Syrquin. Three different data sets are used. Parameter structure for the two income variables seems very different in several quadratic specifications, but the differences become much weaker when implied elasticities at specific income levels are compared or when a simpler specification is adopted. Real income elasticities are expectedly larger than those relative to conventional income, and ratio of the two elasticities appears to rise with income. Real income elasticities are somewhat smaller for 1970s than for 1960s. There is no clear pattern in the elasticities for the full sample and the LDC subsample, although elasticities for the LDCs tend to be slightly higher.
