AB  - This paper describes the crawling/galloping peg as a reaction function to international reserves shocks, aimed at restoring a desired level of reserves. The estimation of devaluation rules for Argentina, Brazil, Chile and Uruguay in the 1970's reveal well defined and systematic characteristics. For example, facing an outflow of reserves, the authorities devalued at a higher rate than the inflation differential between domestic and foreign prices, affecting directly the real exchange rate. That reaction was more than proportional to the changes in reserves, and it was pursued almost exclusively in periods of low reserves.
